GETTING STARTED


🌟 CORE FEATURES

@db-ux/astro is a library and template for building websites using Astro
[https://astro.build/] and the DB UX Design System
[https://design-system.deutschebahn.com/]. It provides a set of components,
layouts and utilities enabling you to build blazingly-fast, accessible and
beautiful websites that follow DB UX Design System guidelines.

Some of the core features include:

 * Very easy installation and updating. No forking or cloning required!
 * Implements the DB UX Design System v3
   [https://design-system.deutschebahn.com/]. You can even directly import DB UI
   React components, allowing for elaborate designs if desired. Follow DB UX
   Design System guidelines out-of-the-box.
 * Responsive by default. Works great on both desktop and mobile devices.
 * Comes with a default layout suitable for most common usecases like
   documentation sites or landing pages.
 * Integrated search functionality using Orama
   [https://docs.orama.com/docs/orama-js].
 * Automatic sitemap generation for better SEO and integration with DB Search
   [https://anonyme-suche.intranet.deutschebahn.com/seb/].
 * Automatic generation of navigation and table of contents for your pages.
 * Write content in Markdown and MDX [https://mdxjs.com/] for maximum
   flexibility and ease of use. Control how your content is rendered using
   Markdown Front Matter attributes.


🚀 GETTING STARTED

To get started with @db-ux/astro, start by creating a new Astro app
[https://docs.astro.build/en/install-and-setup/]. When prompted, we recommend
using the minimal template for best compatibility:

npm create astro@latest

Next, simply navigate into your project directory and use our CLI installer to
add @db-ux/astro to your project. This will automatically install all required
peer dependencies as well:

npm create @db-ux/astro

In your astro.config.mjs, add the integration:

import { defineConfig } from 'astro/config';
import { dbUxAstro } from '@db-ux/astro';

export default defineConfig({
  // Add the dbUxAstro integration
  integrations: [
    dbUxAstro({
      appName: 'my-awesome-website',
    }),
  ],
  // Other Astro configuration options...
});

Finally, start the development server:

npm run dev

You should now see your website running at http://localhost:4321/. And that’s
it! You can now start building your website using @db-ux/astro. Have fun and
make sure to check out the rest of our guides as well as the official Astro
documentation [https://docs.astro.build/]! 🎉


🏗 CREATE YOUR OWN PAGES

We highly recommend using Markdown [https://duckduckgo.com/?q=markdown&ia=web]
to create pages as it’s easy to learn and quick to use.

To create a new Markdown page, simply create a new file with the .md extension
in the src/pages directory. Astro uses a file-based routing system, meaning that
directory and file names will directly be used to build the URL structure of
your website. For example, creating a file at src/pages/my-awesome-page.md will
make it available at http://localhost:4321/my-awesome-page. You can read more
about Astro’s file-based routing in the official documentation
[https://docs.astro.build/en/guides/routing/].


🌄 APPLY STYLING AND DB UX DESIGN SYSTEM

Astro features layouts [https://docs.astro.build/en/basics/layouts/] that allow
apps to share common UI structure and styling across multiple pages.
@db-ux/astro comes with built-in layouts that already include all necessary
styling and structure to get you started quickly. These also implement the DB UX
Design System guidelines out-of-the-box.

For any page to make use of the one of our built-in layouts (e.g. the default
layout [layouts/default]), you need to include the following front matter at the
top of your Markdown or MDX files:

---
layout: '@db-ux/astro/layouts/default'
---

Alternatively, if you’d like to use Astro’s default .astro files, you can set
the layout like this:

---
import DefaultLayout from '@db-ux/astro/layouts/default';
---

<DefaultLayout>
  <!-- Your page content goes here -->
</DefaultLayout>


🧭 MAKE YOUR PAGE AVAILABLE IN THE MAIN NAVIGATION

@db-ux/astro comes with a built-in navigation menu that is included in most
layouts. This navigation allows users to easily browse through the different
pages of your website. As of now, this navigation is not generated
automatically. Instead, you need to manually configure which pages should appear
in the navigation.

To do that, we recommend creating a file app.navigation.ts in the src directory
of your Astro project. In this file, you can define the structure of your
navigation menu by exporting an array of navigation items. For example:

// src/app.navigation.ts
export const navigation: NavigationItem[] = [
  {
    title: 'Guides',
    children: [
      {
        title: 'Getting Started',
        path: '/guides/getting-started',
      },
      {
        title: 'Navigation',
        path: '/guides/navigation',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    title: 'Layouts',
    children: [
      {
        title: 'Default Layout',
        path: '/layouts/default',
      },
    ],
  }
];

You can then import this navigation structure in your astro.config.mjs and pass
it to the integration config:

// astro.config.mjs
import { defineConfig } from 'astro/config';
import { dbUxAstro } from '@db-ux/astro';
import { navigation } from './src/app.navigation';

export default defineConfig({
  integrations: [
    dbUxAstro({
      // Other config options...
      navigation,
    }),
  ],
  // Other config options...
});

Navigation is further explained in the Navigation Guide [guides/navigation].

And that’s all you need to get started with @db-ux/astro! From here, you can
explore more advanced features and customization options in the guides as well
as in the layout and component references. Happy building! 🚀

